    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-08-07T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-08-07T00:00:00-05:00" n="388"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d388">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">812.00/15716½</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to President
                            <persName type="to">Wilson</persName>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-08-07">
                            <hi rend="italic">August 7, 1915</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. President</hi>: I received your telegram of the
                    6th in regard to the effect of Villa’s arbitrary actions upon the work of the
                    conference. The importance of it seems to be that as the preliminary <pb
                        facs="0593" n="547" xml:id="pg_547"/> step was to secure a compromise
                    between factions, it would very much embarrass that plan if Villa should prove
                    himself to be unworthy of consideration by his continued acts of aggression
                    against foreigners.</p>
                <p>Fortunately, however, the situation is much clearer this morning. A despatch from
                        Carothers<note n="14" xml:id="d388fn1">Not printed.</note> states that Villa
                    will remain at El Paso until he has had an interview with General Scott and that
                    the meeting of miners, which he had summoned at Chihuahua, would be postponed
                    until after such interview. Secretary Houston has also consented to the
                    establishment under military decree of cattle inspection upon the border. This
                    will relieve, to a considerable measure, I believe, Villa’s desperate financial
                    situation which has induced his arbitrary conduct.</p>
                <p>Faithfully yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Robert Lansing</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
